AT|

1) should we be in a small slam or grand slam? and 
2) which suit (or NT) is best?|
PG| ***** 113 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As it turns out, 7C is a great contract, but hard to bid. You have 12 top tricks, and will usually be able to set up a long spade with 2 or 3 ruffs for your 13th trick. And if, unluckily, spades don't break 4-3, you can at worst try the diamond finesse.|
PG| ***** 114 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One thing to discuss is Stan's 2nd bid. He is a bit stuck, as he is not sure whether to play in spades, NT, or possibly even clubs. But a new suit is forcing. Personally, when forced to bid a 3-card suit, I tend to prefer bidding a minor, as it is less likely we will end up in that minor even if pard thinks we have a fit, we often end up in NT.|
PG| ***** 115 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So 2D will probably work out a bit better on more hands than 2H. However, the important thing is Stan did bid a new suit, which lets him find out more about the hand. Then correctly bid RKCB to see if we had 7. 7C is very difficult to get to, and it is likely no one would get there.|
PG| ***** 116 ***** |


nt|^B@2
dee_dee_20: After 2@D what will you bid?|
PG| ***** 117 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I bid 2N and we still end up in 6N.|
