nt|^B@2
princesess: Is it then Blackwood or quantitative?|
PG| ***** 121 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Well, as you know, I don't think much of quantitative. If you never play quantitative I think you will do just fine. (As usual, most experts would disagree with me). The problem is you are never sure what is quantitative. If you want to play that as quantitative, then 4C would have to be Gerber. Then you give up 4C as a slam try in clubs. Let me next explain my style. However, you can decide how to play the 4NT i different bidding cycles.|
PG| ***** 122 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Here is my recommendation regarding quantitative 4N.|
PG| ***** 123 ***** |


AT|

Your first choice (and it is a good one) is to never play it as quantitative.|
PG| ***** 124 ***** |


AT| 

Your 2nd choice (which is what I play), is to restrict 4N quantitative to the following 5 auctions:|
PG| ***** 125 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|^e1) 1N-P-4N
^e2) 2N-P-4N
^e3) 2C-P-2D-P-2N-P-4N
^e4) 1x-P-1y-P-1N-P-4N or 
^e5) 1x-P-1Y-P-2N-P-4N|
PG| ***** 126 ***** |


AT|
^B@2That's it. It may not be perfect, but it is completely unambiguous. And btw, 4C in all those auctions is Gerber, and, similarly, is the only time 4C is Gerber.|
PG| ***** 127 ***** |


NT||qx||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to this auction-1C-P-1S-P-2C-P-2D-P-2H-when in other words I bid 2H over 2D. That would not show hearts. It would say I am looking for NT but don't have a heart stopper. Because pard cannot have a 4-card heart suit on that auction (otherwise he would bid 2H over 2C).|
PG| ***** 128 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And if I have hearts, I would bid 2N. So 2H is asking about hearts.|
PG| ***** 129 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, if auction goes as |ht|b|at|^j{|ia|,1CP1SP2DP2NP|at|}|
PG| ***** 130 ***** |


ht|b|at|^u@2then 4NT is RKCB.|
